Default Values for Mooring Elements

Dan Kelley (https://orcid.org/0000-0001-7808-5911)

2021-06-12

Source: vignettes/mooring_elements.Rmd
mooring_elements.Rmd

The data stored in data(mooringElements) were extracted from Dewey’s Matlab matlab file named mdcodes.mat, which were apparently extracted from more primary sources. Neither the provenance and accuracy of individual items was checked before inclusion here.

Dewey reports dimensions in centimetres, but these are converted to metres here.

The column names are not the same as Dewey uses. The meaning of the final column is unknown, so it is just called code here, and its values are not are used in this package.

Anchor characteristics

The buoyancy values are in kg and the height values are in m. Note that the values shown below have no affect on the computation of mooring knockdown.

name buoyancy height source originalName
trainwheel -1000 0 kelley NA

Chain characteristics

The buoyancyPerMeter values are in kg/m, while height and width are in m, and CD is unitless. The code values are listed for data from Dewey only, and they are not used in this package.

Connector characteristics

The buoyancy values are in kg, while height and width are in m, and CD is unitless. Not all data sources list height and width (or comparable values) and so zeros are used in such instances. Since the only use of these values in the package are to compute area, for a drag calculation, and since the drag on floats and wires is likely to exceed that on small elements, this zeroing-out may not pose a large problem. The code values are listed for data from Dewey only, and they are not used in this package.

Wire characteristics

The buoyancyPerMeter values are in kg/m, while diameter is in m, and CD is unitless. The code values are listed for data from Dewey only, and they are not used in this package.

Note that Dewey sets diameter to 0 for wires, saves diameter in a width field, and lists a nonsense value for height. These are signals that let his code distinguish between floats, wires, etc., but the present package handles this differently.
